Database replication improves availability and read performance by maintaining multiple copies of the same data.

There are two primary replication strategies:

Synchronous Replication

In synchronous replication, data is written to the primary database and all replicas before the transaction is considered complete.

Advantages:

Strong consistency
No stale reads
Suitable for financial systems

Disadvantages:

Higher latency
Slower write performance
Reduced availability if replicas become unreachable
Asynchronous Replication

In asynchronous replication, the primary database confirms the write immediately and sends updates to replicas afterward.

Advantages:

Faster writes
Better availability
Lower latency

Disadvantages:

Temporary replication delay
Users may read outdated data
Possible data loss if the primary fails before replication completes

Choosing between synchronous and asynchronous replication depends on business requirements.

Examples:

Banking applications often prefer synchronous replication.
Social media platforms commonly use asynchronous replication.

Key Points

Replication creates multiple copies of data.
Synchronous replication prioritizes consistency.
Asynchronous replication prioritizes performance and availability.
Replication improves fault tolerance and read scalability.